Author-Name: Douglas W. Diamond 
Title: Presidential Address, Committing to Commit: Short-term Debt When Enforcement Is Costly 
Abstract:
 In legal systems with expensive or ineffective contract enforcement, it is
 difficult to induce lenders to enforce debt contracts. If lenders do not
 enforce, borrowers will have incentives to misbehave. Lenders have
 incentives to enforce given bad news when debt is short-term and subject
 to runs caused by externalities across lenders. Lenders will not undo
 these externalities by negotiation. The required number of lenders
 increases with enforcement costs. A very high enforcement cost can exceed
 the ex ante incentive benefit of enforcement. Removing lenders' right to
 immediately enforce their debt with a "bail-in" can improve the ex ante
 incentives of borrowers. Copyright 2004 by The American Finance Association. 
